WRITING.TITLE: To answer some questions
WRITING.TEXT: I see many people(particularly teenagers) who are concerned about their height asking if they can still grow and what factors affect their growth @ r/tall 1. Does Lack of nutrition affect height growth? Yes, but it is not the " I'm a picky eater" kind of lack of nutrition, the kind of nutrition I'm talking about is literally North korea level of malnourishment, which is unlikely in our current generation and for most of us here in reddit. If you've never starved before albeit however less you eat, it doesn't matter. There are people who are 6'3 and 120lbs in r/tall 2. Does lack of sleep affect height growth? Yes. Growth hormones are released during our sleep, so if you've slept below 3-4 hours every night than it is likely you stunt your growth. You should be getting at least 6 hours of sleep on average, which applies for an adult too for healthy living 3. Why am I shorter than my father/siblings? Genes work in different ways, you could be totally inheriting your height from a shorter parent. whilst your sibling got the taller end, or even from a grandparent/great grandparent. Having 2 tall parents does increase your chance of being tall as compared to someone who have 1 short/1 tall parent 4. Does playing basketball make you grow taller? There is no evidence that it does, however high intensive exercise is known to promote hgh according to some scientific articles, so exercising/playing sports may make you grow a bit taller..this is still controversial 5. Does weightlifting stunt growth during puberty? Nope, weightlifting it self does not stunt growth. However if you injured your growth plates by lifting too heavy for your body weight or doing improper form, than there is a chance it can, so do practice proper techniques while exercising 6. Does over masturbating during puberty stunt growth? Don't get me started on this, there is no scientific evidence that shows it does, and from personal experience...NO 7. When do I stopped growing? On average, males stop having growth spurts after 16, and they grow a few more inches till they are 18. After 18 majority of guys do not have any noticeable growth( gt;2inches). however there are a few who do grow till their early 20s and even have growth spurts but they are incredibly rare.

Nope, weight lifting itself doesn #8217;t stunt growth. However if you injure your growth plates while lifting by lifting too heavy or doing improper form, than there is a chance it can. Try to practice proper techniques and not go too heavy
